const P = {
thename:{name:"„Gott dank“ · the name itself",conf:"verified",years:"1700s → today",place:"Hanau → Galicia → the world",rel:"Origin of the surname",facts:{Meaning:"'Thank God', German & Yiddish",Family:"The name passed through a WOMAN, Gittel's husband took HER surname at marriage",Shtetl:"Isterik (Yiddish) = Ustrzyki Dolne, SE Galicia, the documented origin town of the Vaytman-Gottdank / Israel line",Decree:"1787, Emperor Joseph II required all Galician Jews to adopt fixed German surnames by January 1788",Earliest:"A 'Hanau (Gottdank)' family in 1700s Germany, but that cluster traces to Lorraine, so its link to the Galician Gottdanks is unproven"},story:["In 1787 the Emperor Joseph II ordered every Jew in Galicia to take a fixed German surname by the new year. You could choose your own or be handed one. 'Gottdank' is two plain German words for 'thank God', the kind of name a family picks when the choosing is theirs, though whether ours did the choosing nobody wrote down.","The town was Isterik, the Yiddish name for Ustrzyki Dolne, in the far southeastern corner of old Galicia where the land folds up into the Bieszczady. Jews had lived there since the 1600s. A census in 1765 counted 162 of them, and by 1900 they were 61 percent of the town. This is where the odd thing about the name happened, and it happened twice. Kalman married Gittel the midwife and took her surname instead of handing her his. Down the same streets, Abraham Vaytman married a Miriam Gottdank and did the same. The name came down through the women.","Their children carried it out, to New York, to Ottawa, to São Paulo. The Jews who stayed were shot at the cemetery or sent to Belzec, and Isterik has none now. A 'Hanau Gottdank' family turns up in 1700s Germany too, but that line traces to Lorraine, so whether it touches ours is anyone's guess. What's certain is smaller and stranger. Every Gottdank in this tree is carrying a Galician woman's name."],src:["Family document: 'Gottdank Descendants'","JewishGen Lesko Yizkor (Isterik = Ustrzyki Dolne)","Virtual Shtetl (sztetl.org.pl): Ustrzyki Dolne community history","Habsburg Edict on Jewish Names, July 23, 1787","Forebears (surname distribution)","Geni (Hanau & Vaytman-Gottdank)"]},
gittel:{name:"Gittel Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"19th c.",place:"Galicia (the Isterik region)",rel:"Generation One · the matriarch whose name the family carries",facts:{Trade:"Midwife, 'like her female ancestors'",Yiddish:"In Yiddish the word for midwife, bobe, is also the word for grandmother",Husband:"Kalman ('Coleman')",Surname:"On her son Charles's 1909 marriage record she is 'Gitte Bernfeld', so her maiden name may be Bernfeld (Berenfeld)",America:"Never emigrated",Rest:"Said to be buried in Pápa, Hungary, but no record confirms it; treat as family memory"},story:["Gittel caught babies in Galicia, the way her mother and grandmother had before her. In Yiddish the word for midwife and the word for grandmother were the same word, bobe. The family tells it that Gottdank was her name, that Kalman took it when they married, and that her children carried it out of the shtetl to Chicago and New York.","She never crossed the ocean. Her son Charles's 1909 New York marriage record names her 'Gitte Bernfeld', which leaves open whether the Gottdank name came down through her birth family or reached her some other way.","There was another midwife. Maryem Gottdank of Isterik was killed when the town's Jews were sent to Bełżec in 1942, and her granddaughter, the Yiddish scholar Miriam Gottdank Isaacs, drew her from memory. Whether Maryem was Gittel's daughter, her cousin, or just another woman with the same rare name and the same trade in the same small town, the records haven't closed it. Gittel never left, but the name did. If the family has it right, it was always hers to give, the bobe whose name they still carry."],gap:"A 1909 record names her 'Gitte Bernfeld,' so her maiden name may be Bernfeld (Berenfeld), and which spouse was born 'Gottdank' is contested. The Pápa burial stays unverified; the midwife Maryem Gottdank of Isterik is the best lead to her European life.",src:["Family document, Generation 1","NYC marriage record, 1909 (son Charles, mother 'Gitte Bernfeld')","JewishGen Lesko Yizkor (Isterik)","Jewish Women's Archive, Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik","Jewish Women's Archive, 'Women Religious Workers in Eastern Europe' (Yiddish bobe = midwife and grandmother)","Bełżec deportation list (Sanok district, Sept 1942)"]},
coleman:{name:"Kalman ('Coleman') Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"d. before 1900",place:"Galicia (Isterik)",rel:"Generation One · Charles's father",facts:{Name:"Confirmed as 'Kalman Gottdank' on his son Charles's 1909 marriage record",Etymology:"Kalman is the Yiddish form of Kalonymos (Ancient Greek: 'beautiful name'), an Ashkenazic name traced to the medieval Rhineland; its recorded American equivalent is Coleman",Died:"Before Bernhard & Bertha's 1900 wedding",Surname:"On the record he carries the Gottdank name; family lore says he took it from Gittel at marriage",Shtetl:"By the 1880s Jews were the majority in Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne); a railway reached the town in 1872"},story:["The one piece of paper that survives gives his name as Kalman Gottdank, set down when his son Charles married in New York in 1909, and that's nearly all of him there is. Kalman is the Yiddish short of Kalonymos, which is Greek for 'beautiful name', a name carried through Ashkenaz since the medieval Rhineland.","He lived his whole life in Isterik, the shtetl tucked into the far southeast corner of Galicia, and he caught the town on its way up. The railway came through in 1872 and tied the place to Przemyśl and Sanok, and by the 1880s the Jews were the majority there, more of them merchants than anything else. He died before the century turned, before his sons ever crossed to New York and Chicago.","Kalman has an English twin, Coleman, the kind of swap his sons' generation made once they were across the water. Kalman never crossed. Generations on, a boy in this family got named Cole. Nobody set out to carry the first ancestor's name down. It came down anyway."],src:["Family document, Generation 1","NYC marriage record, 1909 (son Charles, father 'Kalman Gottdank')","Virtual Shtetl (sztetl.org.pl): Ustrzyki Dolne community history","Geneanet / Behind the Name (Kalman · Kalonymos · Coleman)"]},
charles:{name:"Charles Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"late 1800s – 1957",place:"Galicia → Brooklyn, NY",rel:"Gittel & Coleman's son · the New York barber",facts:{Trade:"Barber, New York",Parents:"Kalman Gottdank & Gitte Bernfeld, the 'Coleman & Gittel' of family memory, Generation One",Married:"Fanny Krantz, in Manhattan, 1909",Immigrated:"From Galicia via Ellis Island; naturalized in New York, 1912",Children:"Lillian · Helen · Jerry (Jerome) · MILTON",Census:"Brooklyn in the 1940 census, with Fannie and Milton",Died:"September 25, 1957, buried Flushing, Queens"},story:["Charles Gottdank made his living with a razor. Back in the Galicia he left, better than half the barbers were Jews, so a boy learning to strop a blade was nothing anyone gave a second look. He carried the trade across the water to New York, where immigrant barbers like him were busy building unions of their own.","He married Fanny Krantz in New York in 1909, and by 1912 he had his citizenship papers in hand, a citizen well before the family was finished. Jerry came first, in 1911. Then the two girls, Lillian and Helen, and last of all Milton in 1921. By 1940 the older three had gone off into lives of their own, and it was just Charles, Fannie, and the youngest boy in the Brooklyn flat.","He'd come out of Isterik, the shtetl in far southeast Galicia his parents never left, son of Kalman and Gittel, the Coleman and Gittel of family memory. He died on the twenty-fifth of September, 1957, and was buried in Flushing, Queens. His mother and father never crossed the ocean. Charles did, and the name crossed with him."],src:["Family document, Generations 2–3","NYC marriage record, 1909 (parents Kalman Gottdank & Gitte Bernfeld; wife Fanny Krantz)","1940 US Census, Brooklyn","New York naturalization, 1912","Find A Grave (Charles Gottdank, d. 1957, Flushing, Queens)","Wikipedia, Galician Jews (over 65% of barbers in Galicia were Jewish)","jewishcurrents.org, 'A Short History of Jews in the American Labor Movement' (Jewish barbers organized their own unions in New York)"]},
fannieK:{name:"Fannie (Krantz) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1894 – 1972",place:"Bronx, NY",rel:"Charles's wife · Generation Two",facts:{Parents:"Jacob Krantz ⚭ Martha Feit",Married:"Charles, in Manhattan, 1909",Match:"SSDI 'Fanny Gottdank, b. Apr 20 1894, d. 1972'; buried at New Montefiore Cemetery, West Babylon",Children:"Lillian · Helen · Jerry · Milton"},story:["Fannie Krantz was fifteen the year she married Charles Gottdank, a barber lately come from Galicia. She was a Bronx girl, born April 20, 1894, wed in Manhattan in 1909. Her own people were Krantzes, her father Jacob, her mother Martha Feit.","The children came across ten long years. Jerry first, in 1911, when she was barely seventeen, then the two girls, Lillian and Helen, and last of all Milton in 1921. By the 1940 census the older three had scattered into lives of their own, and the Brooklyn flat held just the three of them, Charles, Fannie, and the youngest boy. Charles died in the fall of 1957. Fannie kept going fifteen more years without him.","She married into a name and held the family, and now she holds the ground. She lies at New Montefiore out in West Babylon, the Long Island cemetery that opened its gates in 1928, and two of her grandchildren, Lynn Jay and Kurt, both lost young, were laid in the family plot close beside her."],gap:"A different Fannie Gottdank turns up in the records (d. 1967, Flushing), not her. Hers is the New Montefiore grave, 1894–1972.",src:["Family document","SSDI (Fanny, 1894-1972)","Find A Grave Index (New Montefiore Cemetery, West Babylon)","Wikipedia, New Montefiore Cemetery (founded 1928)"]},
lillian:{name:"Lillian (Gottdank) Johnson",conf:"verified",years:"20th c.",place:"New York · Bronx",rel:"Charles & Fannie's daughter · Milton's sister",facts:{Parents:"Charles Gottdank (the barber) ⚭ Fannie Krantz",Eldest:"First of Charles & Fannie's four (Lillian, Helen, Jerry, Milton)",FirstHusband:"Morris Birnbaum",Children:"Ira · June",Remarried:"Became Lillian Johnson",Son:"Ira Birnbaum: De Witt Clinton HS (Bronx), into Lehigh at 16, Merchant Marine in the South Pacific WWII; d. age 94, wife Marilyn, sons Jesse & Eric"},story:["Charles Gottdank cut hair in New York and was raising four kids in Brooklyn, and Lillian came first, ahead of Helen and Jerry and little Milton. She married Morris Birnbaum, and by the time their son Ira was at De Witt Clinton High the family had moved up to the Bronx, a borough away from her father's shop. There were two with Morris, Ira and a daughter June. Ira was the bright one, into Lehigh at sixteen and off to the South Pacific with the Merchant Marine.","Then she married again and became a Johnson. The barber's oldest girl carried his name out of Brooklyn and wore it down through three: Gottdank, then Birnbaum, then Johnson, one Bronx woman and the whole trail behind her."],src:["Family document, Generation 4","Ira Birnbaum obituary, New York Times / Legacy.com, Jan 2022 (De Witt Clinton HS; Lehigh Univ., entered age 16; Merchant Marine South Pacific WWII; wife Marilyn 71 years, sons Jesse and Eric; d. age 94)"]},
helenS:{name:"Helen (Gottdank) Stober",conf:"verified",years:"20th c.",place:"New York",rel:"Charles & Fannie's daughter · Milton's sister",facts:{Husband:"Leo Stober",Children:"Judy Wahrman (née Stober) · Marvin Stober",Note:"'We were very friendly with Helen and her husband Leo', the document",JudysHusband:"Ralph Wahrman (1939-2011), NYC native; Stuyvesant HS · Queens College BA · Michigan State PhD; sociology professor at BGSU for 34 years; edited Sociological Focus (journal of NCSA) from 1988; d. Sept 30 2011; children Francine · Eric · Anna",Marvin:"Special Education lecturer, City College of New York (CUNY)"},story:["'We were very friendly with Helen and her husband Leo,' the document says, and that one line is most of what came down about her.","Her father Charles cut hair in New York, and his four kids grew up and scattered into homes of their own, Helen and Lillian and Jerry and Milton. Helen married Leo Stober. They had Judy and Marvin. Judy married Ralph Wahrman and raised Francine, Eric, and Anna. Marvin spent his life in a classroom.","The dates and the diplomas are all in the record. The thing that outlasted them is that plainest line. Helen and Leo were people you wanted to be near."],src:["Family document, Generations 3–4","Sentinel-Tribune (Bowling Green, OH), 1 Oct 2011: Ralph Wahrman obituary (wife Judith Stober; NYC native; Stuyvesant HS; Queens College; Michigan State PhD; BGSU 34 years; d. 30 Sept 2011, age 71)","BGSU Retirees newsletter, Nov 2011 (Ralph Wahrman, emeritus prof. of sociology)","ASA Footnotes, Sept/Oct 2013 (Wahrman became editor of Sociological Focus in 1988)","CUNY Academic Commons / Rate My Professors (Marvin Stober, Education, City College of New York)"]},
jerry:{name:"Jerry (Jerome) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1911 – 1993",place:"New York → Spring Valley, NY → Miami Beach, FL",rel:"Charles & Fannie's son · Milton's brother",facts:{Born:"October 19, 1911, New York, the eldest of Charles & Fannie's four",Wife:"Molly (1910–2011); she outlived him by eighteen years, reaching 101",Children:"Frank · Alan · Linda",Settled:"Spring Valley, Rockland County, NY (postwar NYC-Jewish migration)",Retired:"Miami Beach, FL",Match:"SSDI: Jerome Gottdank, b. Oct 19 1911, d. Dec 22 1993, Miami Beach"},story:["Jerry came first. October 19, 1911, the eldest of the barber's four, born in New York a full year before his father Charles had citizenship in hand. Jerome on every official page, Jerry to anyone who actually knew him.","He married Molly, a Brooklyn girl born the year before him. When the war ended they did the thing half of Jewish New York was doing, and they moved up to Rockland County, to Spring Valley, and let Frank and Alan and Linda grow up with grass instead of pavement. The boroughs stayed an hour south. Close enough to visit, far enough to be its own life.","When the working years ran out he went to Miami Beach, the warm last chapter so much of old New York moved toward, and he died there three days before Christmas in 1993, eighty-two. Molly never followed him south. She stayed on in Spring Valley another eighteen years, all the way to a hundred and one. He came first into the family. She stayed in it longest."],src:["SSDI: Jerome Gottdank, b. Oct 19 1911, d. Dec 22 1993, Miami Beach","SSDI: Molly Gottdank, b. Mar 31 1910, d. Apr 21 2011, Spring Valley, NY","AncientFaces Gottdank surname records (ancientfaces.com/surname/gottdank-family-history/14053)","Encyclopedia.com, 'Rockland County' (postwar Jewish families from NYC relocated to Spring Valley and Rockland County)","Find A Grave / family document (Charles & Fannie's children: Lillian, Helen, Jerry, Milton; Jerry the eldest, b. 1911)"]},
mollyR:{name:"Molly Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1910 – 2011",place:"Brooklyn → Spring Valley, NY",rel:"Jerry's wife · mother of Frank, Alan & Linda",facts:{Born:"March 31, 1910, Brooklyn",Died:"April 21, 2011, Spring Valley, NY, aged 101",Husband:"Jerry (Jerome), 1911–1993",Children:"Frank(lin) · Alan · Linda",Settled:"Spring Valley, Rockland County, NY (postwar)"},story:["Molly was a Brooklyn girl, born there on March 31, 1910, a year ahead of the man she'd marry. Jerry was the barber's eldest son, and for the early stretch their life was the city's life, the close blocks and family in every direction.","When the war ended they did what half of Jewish New York was doing and bought up into Rockland County, to Spring Valley, where Frank and Alan and Linda grew up with lawns instead of stoops. The boroughs sat an hour south, near enough to visit and far enough to be their own.","Jerry took the warm last chapter down in Miami Beach and died there three days before Christmas in 1993. Molly didn't go south. She stayed on in Spring Valley, year after year, until she'd outlived him by eighteen and outlasted the century she was born into. A hundred and one years, and nearly all of them New York."],src:["Family document","SSDI: Molly Gottdank, b. Mar 31 1910, d. Apr 21 2011, Spring Valley, NY","SSDI: Jerome Gottdank, b. Oct 19 1911, d. Dec 22 1993, Miami Beach","Encyclopedia.com, 'Rockland County' (postwar Jewish families from NYC relocated to Spring Valley and Rockland County)","Radaris relative listings (confirmed)"]},
franklin:{name:"Franklin D. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"b. ~1955",place:"Spring Valley, NY → Lewes, DE",rel:"Son of Jerry & Molly",facts:{Wife:"Wendy",Parents:"Jerry ⚭ Molly, per the family document ('Frank')",Lived:"Spring Valley & Monsey, NY; Selbyville area, DE; now Lewes, DE",Home:"Mariners' Retreat, Lewes (Samantha Drive); two-story, ~3,600 sq ft; built and moved in March 2020; outdoor shower reached only through a glass door at the back of the indoor shower"},story:["Frank in the family, Franklin to the records, Jerry and Molly's son, which makes him first cousin to Brian and Dale. He grew up in Spring Valley, the Rockland County town his parents reached coming up out of Brooklyn after the war, and he stayed in that corner of New York, through Monsey, before he and Wendy went south.","They tried southern Delaware first, the flat country near the Maryland line around Selbyville. Then they decided to build. On Samantha Drive, at Mariners' Retreat in Lewes, they drew the house they wanted, two stories and thirty-six hundred square feet, with one idea that was theirs alone. The only way to the outdoor shower is a glass door at the back of the indoor one. They moved in March 2020, just as the world bolted its doors. Theirs opened to the sky. From fifty degrees up, rain or shine, that's where they go, sun in the afternoon and the stars at night."],src:["Family document (son 'Frank')","Delaware Beach Life, 'Getting Outdoors' cottage tour: Wendy & Frank Gottdank, Mariners' Retreat, Lewes; two-story, ~3,600 sq ft; prior Selbyville-area home; only access to the outdoor shower is a glass door at the back of the indoor shower; used from 50 degrees up, rain or shine; moved in March 2020","Radaris (Franklin Gottdank, b. ~1955, age 71 in 2026; 406 Samantha Dr, Lewes DE; Molly relative listing; prior addresses 230 Kearsing Pkwy Monsey NY & 21 David Dr Spring Valley NY)","LocateFamily (household with Wendy)"]},
wendy:{name:"Wendy Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Spring Valley, NY → Selbyville, DE → Lewes, DE",rel:"Wife of Franklin",facts:{Household:"21 David Drive, Spring Valley NY (with Franklin); then Selbyville area, DE; now Mariners' Retreat, Lewes DE",Garden:"Fills the pots, planters and window boxes with flowers each summer at the Lewes house",MistAway:"MistAway mosquito misting system at the Selbyville home by at least 2015",OutdoorShower:"Her design idea for the Lewes build: glass door inside the indoor shower opens directly to an open-air outdoor shower with no roof; used from 50 degrees up, rain or not",Lewes:"Mariners' Retreat sits in the heart of Lewes off 2nd and 4th Streets, near the Lewes-Rehoboth Canal and within a couple miles of the beach and Cape Henlopen"},story:["The pots run over with flowers, planters and window boxes too, every last one of them Wendy's doing at the house in Mariners' Retreat. She and Frank took the long way to that garden. First Spring Valley, the Rockland County town his family reached after Brooklyn once the war was over. Then south to the flat country near the Maryland line, the Selbyville place, where by 2015 they had a MistAway running to keep the mosquitoes down.","When they built in Lewes, just off 2nd Street with the canal and Cape Henlopen close by, the outdoor shower was hers. She wanted it tied straight to the house, so a glass door at the back of the indoor shower swings open to open air with no roof above it. Fifty degrees and up, rain or shine, that's where they go, sun in the afternoon and stars at night. They moved in March 2020, just as the world shut, and they still walk into old Lewes for the Saturday market. Flower boxes, a shower open to the sky, every piece of that house she shaped the same way. She's the one who keeps letting the weather in."],src:["Delaware Beach Life, 'Getting Outdoors' cottage tour: Wendy & Frank Gottdank, Mariners' Retreat Lewes; Wendy's design: glass door in indoor shower opens to outdoor shower (no roof); 50 degrees and up; moved March 2020; prior Selbyville-area home; Wendy fills the pots, planters and window boxes with flowers; walk to Lewes and farmers market","Mariners' Retreat Lewes (marinersretreatlewes.com / activeadultsdelaware.com): luxury community of single-family homesites in the heart of Lewes off 2nd/4th Streets, near the Lewes-Rehoboth Canal, within ~2 miles of Lewes Beach and Cape Henlopen State Park","Lawns Unlimited (lawnsunlimited.com/wendy-gottdank/): Wendy review, 'The MistAway system really works! We had hardly any insects bother us last summer. Just signed up again for 2016'","Radaris address pairing: 21 David Drive Spring Valley NY + Lewes DE"]},
allan:{name:"Allan M. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"~1939 – 2025",place:"Brooklyn → Spring Valley, NY → Manhattan UWS",rel:"Son of Jerry & Molly",facts:{Parents:"Jerry ⚭ Molly, the document's 'Alan'",Education:"Brooklyn College, Class of 1960",Home:"161 W 61st St (The Alfred), Lincoln Center, Manhattan",Died:"~March 2025, Ridgewood Chapels, NY",Siblings:"Frank(lin) · Linda"},story:["Brooklyn College wrote him down as Allan M. Gottdank, Class of 1960. At home he was Alan. He was one of Jerry and Molly's three, raised in Spring Valley after the family came up from Brooklyn, into the Rockland County towns where New York Jewish families landed after the war. He had a brother, Frank, and a sister, Linda.","He made his life in Manhattan. Home was 161 West 61st Street, The Alfred, a tower that rose beside Lincoln Center in 1987, and he held to the Upper West Side for decades. Two spellings of one name, the Allan on the diploma and the Alan his people called him, and in the end both belonged to the same man. He died in 2025, and Morton Funeral Home at Ridgewood Chapels handled the arrangements. Franklin and Linda outlived him."],src:["Brooklyn College In Memoriam (lists 'Allan M. Gottdank '60', deaths reported Apr-Nov 2025): brooklyn.edu/alumni/in-memoriam-13-1/","locatefamily.com (Allan M. Gottdank, 161 W 61st St, NY, captured 2019)","mortonridgewood.com (Ridgewood Chapels, Queens)","cityrealty.com (The Alfred, 161 W 61st: 38-story condo opened 1987, Lincoln Center district, designed Jung/Brannen Associates)","jerry/mollyR tree entries (family settled Spring Valley after the war; Franklin entry confirms Spring Valley upbringing)","Encyclopedia.com, Rockland County (postwar Jewish families from NYC to Spring Valley, cited in jerry entry)"]},
lindaJ:{name:"Linda Gottdank",conf:"likely",years:"living",place:"Spring Valley, NY",rel:"Daughter of Jerry & Molly",facts:{Parents:"Jerry (Jerome) ⚭ Molly",Siblings:"Frank(lin) · the late Alan"},story:["Jerry and Molly had three, and the family kept them in one order: Frank, Alan, Linda. They'd come up from Brooklyn after the war, into Spring Valley, part of that wave of New York Jewish families who traded the boroughs for lawns in Rockland County in the postwar years. Linda grew up there, the city an hour south.","The name is rare enough that almost anyone who carries it surfaces somewhere. Linda is the one who doesn't. Her father sits in the Social Security index, her mother beside him at a hundred and one, her brother Alan in a Brooklyn College memorial the year he died. When Alan went in 2025, the notice named the two who outlived him, his brother Franklin and his sister Linda, and that one line is the clearest public mark she has. She's still here, the last of the three names, the Gottdank the records never caught."],gap:"No independently matched record yet.",src:["Family document, Generation 4 (lists Frank, Alan, and Linda as Jerry & Molly's children)","Encyclopedia.com, 'Rockland County' (postwar Jewish families from NYC to Spring Valley; also cited in jerry entry)","allan entry (Brooklyn College In Memoriam, 2025; 'His brother Franklin and his sister Linda outlived him')"]},
milton:{name:"Milton Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1921 – 1984",place:"Coney Island, Brooklyn, NY",rel:"Charles & Fannie's youngest son",facts:{Born:"February 28, 1921, New York",Parents:"Charles (the barber) ⚭ Fannie Krantz",Siblings:"Lillian · Helen (Stober) · Jerry",Census:"Still in the Brooklyn household with Charles and Fannie in 1940, the last of the four at home",Home:"West 5th Street, Coney Island, Brooklyn",Wife:"Phyllis Schraeter",Children:"Dale · Brian · Lynn Jay & Kurt (lost as toddlers)",Died:"August 1, 1984"},story:["In the spring of 1940 the census-taker found him at nineteen, still under his father's roof in Brooklyn. He was the last of Charles and Fannie's four, the baby of the house, while Lillian and Helen and Jerry had gone off into lives of their own. He'd been born February 28, 1921, a New Yorker by birth in a family that had crossed an ocean to make him one.","He married Phyllis Schraeter, and they made their home on West 5th Street in Coney Island, a few blocks from the boardwalk and the Atlantic, in a stretch of Brooklyn that had been Jewish since before he was born. They had four children.","They lost two of them young. Lynn Jay died in the spring of 1953, not yet three. Kurt died in June 1961, at two. Both lie in the Mandel Family Circle at New Montefiore, the ground that belonged to Phyllis's own people. Dale grew up in the flat by the water, and Brian likely did too.","Milton died on the first of August, 1984, at sixty-three. The youngest of the barber's four, the last one left at home, and the one whose sons carried the name on."],src:["Family document, Generations 3–4","1940 US Census, Brooklyn","SSDI (1921–1984, NY)","LocateFamily (West 5th Street household record)","My Jewish Learning, 'Jews in Coney Island: A History' (Jewish families in Coney Island since the 1910s)","Find A Grave, Lynn Jay Gottdank (memorial 151784528); Kurt Gottdank (memorial 151738023)"]},
phyllis:{name:"Phyllis (Schraeter) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"c. 1922 – 2012",place:"Brooklyn, NY",rel:"Milton's wife",facts:{Maiden:"SCHRAETER, the 'S' in her directory listing",Parents:"Jacob Schraeter ⚭ Bertha Blazer",School:"Her mother, Bertha Blazer Schraeter, co-founded the Shulamith School for Girls at 4910 14th Ave, Borough Park, in 1930, with Nacha Rivkin and Rabbi M.G. Volk; the first Orthodox Jewish elementary school for girls in North America",Grandparents:"Aaron Schraeter ⚭ Sara Guttman · Wolf Blazer ⚭ Hannah Mandel",Deeper:"David Schraeter · Feivush Gutman ⚭ Hannah Leah · Hersh Mandel ⚭ Ida",Died:"Oct 19, 2012, aged 90",Rest:"New Montefiore, the Mandel Family Circle plot, near her two children"},story:["Bertha Blazer Schraeter opened a school in 1930. With Nacha Rivkin and Rabbi M.G. Volk she started the Shulamith School for Girls at 4910 14th Avenue in Borough Park, the first Orthodox Jewish elementary school for girls in North America. Phyllis was about eight then, a girl in a stretch of Brooklyn where the question of whether daughters deserved a real Jewish education had just been answered, by her own family, with a yes.","She was a Schraeter, Galician on every side, the lines running back through Blazer and Guttman and Mandel. When she married Milton Gottdank she crossed the borough to the water, to the apartment on West 5th Street a few blocks from the Coney Island boardwalk, and they had four children there.","Two of the four they lost young. Lynn Jay died in 1953, not yet three. Kurt died in 1961, at two. Phyllis buried them both in the Mandel Family Circle at New Montefiore, her mother's people's ground. She outlived Milton by almost thirty years and died in 2012, at ninety, and they laid her in that same plot, beside the children she had carried there. The woman whose mother had opened a school for girls came home to her own family's ground."],src:["Family document","Wikipedia, Shulamith School for Girls (founded 1930, Borough Park, Brooklyn)","Find A Grave, Lynn Jay Gottdank (memorial 151784528); Kurt Gottdank (memorial 151738023), New Montefiore Cemetery","New Montefiore Cemetery (Phyllis, Mandel Family Circle)"]},
lostKids:{name:"Lynn Jay & Kurt, lost young",conf:"likely",years:"d. 1953 & 1961, as toddlers",place:"New Montefiore Cemetery, West Babylon, NY",rel:"Children of Milton & Phyllis · Brian and Dale's siblings",facts:{Lynn:"Lynn Jay Gottdank, b. Oct 9, 1950, d. May 31, 1953; her stone reads simply 'DAUGHTER'",Kurt:"Kurt Gottdank, b. 1959, d. June 5, 1961 (age 2), marked 'Child'",Plot:"Both in Section 4, Block 11 at New Montefiore, the Mandel Family Circle, the burial society of Phyllis's mother's family (the Mandels)"},story:["Lynn Jay was born on the ninth of October, 1950, in the flat on West 5th Street near the Coney Island boardwalk. She died on the last day of May, 1953, not yet three. Kurt came years after, born in 1959, and died on the fifth of June, 1961, at two. Her stone says only 'DAUGHTER'. His says 'Child'.","They lie together at New Montefiore, Section 4, Block 11, in the Mandel Family Circle, the burial ground of Phyllis's mother's people. Milton and Phyllis had four, and the other two grew up. The babies were laid among the family, and their brothers, Brian and Dale, carried the name on."],gap:"As close to proven as it gets short of a record naming the parents: two Gottdank children of the right years, in Phyllis's family's own (Mandel) burial plot.",src:["Find A Grave, Lynn Jay Gottdank (memorial 151784528)","Find A Grave, Kurt Gottdank (memorial 151738023), New Montefiore Cemetery"]},
brian:{name:"Brian R. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Brooklyn → Downingtown, PA → Johns Island, SC",rel:"Son of Milton & Phyllis",facts:{Parents:"Milton Gottdank ⚭ Phyllis Schraeter, West 5th Street, Coney Island, Brooklyn",Wife:"Laurie (née Cassidy)",Children:"Cole · Annalyn · Bridget",Household:"403 Santillo Way, Downingtown, PA 19335, since 2001",Now:"Johns Island, South Carolina"},story:["Milton and Phyllis raised their family in a Coney Island apartment on West 5th Street, near the boardwalk and the Atlantic, and that's likely where Brian came up. By 2001 he and Laurie Cassidy had landed somewhere altogether different, 403 Santillo Way in Downingtown, a Chester County borough out in the exurbs west of Philadelphia. There they settled and raised their three.","Cole, Annalyn, and Bridget grew up in that house. Cole and Bridget both drove the fifteen minutes south to West Chester University. Bridget made aliyah to Israel, and Cole went to San Francisco and co-founded a tech startup that went through Y Combinator. With the kids grown, Brian and Laurie pulled up and went south themselves, to Johns Island, the Lowcountry sea island outside Charleston. A boy who likely came up by one ocean spent his middle years inland, then took Laurie back to the water."],src:["LocateFamily (403 Santillo Way, Downingtown, PA, listed since 2001)","Public people-records: Annalyn Gottdank listing (parents Brian R & Laurie A (Cassidy) Gottdank)","Milton / Phyllis entries (West 5th Street, Coney Island; family raised there)","Laurie entry (Johns Island, SC relocation confirmed)"]},
laurie:{name:"Laurie Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Downingtown, PA → Johns Island, SC",rel:"Wife of Brian (household record)",facts:{MaidenName:"Cassidy",Household:"403 Santillo Way, Downingtown, PA, since 2001",Children:"Cole · Annalyn · Bridget",Education:"Pace University, Lubin School of Business",Work:"Human resources, clinical research",Volunteer:"Downingtown Area School District; All4Paws Animal Rescue",Now:"Johns Island, South Carolina"},story:["Laurie married Brian and raised three kids with him, Cole, Annalyn, and Bridget, in the house on Santillo Way in Downingtown. The family settled at that address in 2001 and stayed, out in the Chester County exurbs west of Philadelphia, the kind of borough where you know the school and the back roads and the people at the rescue.","She was a Cassidy before she married, trained at Pace University, and spent her working years in human resources. Around town she gave time to the Downingtown school district and to All4Paws Animal Rescue. When the kids were grown she and Brian went south to Johns Island, the big Lowcountry sea island outside Charleston, trading the Philadelphia exurbs for the marsh and the live oaks."],src:["linkedin.com/in/lauriegottdank (human resources, clinical research; Pace University Lubin School of Business; Downingtown Area School District and All4Paws Animal Rescue volunteer)","LocateFamily (403 Santillo Way, Downingtown PA, listed since 2001)","brian entry (wife Laurie née Cassidy; children Cole, Annalyn, Bridget; Johns Island, SC)"]},
cole:{name:"Cole Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"b. ~1997",place:"Downingtown, PA → San Francisco, CA",rel:"Son of Brian & Laurie",facts:{Raised:"403 Santillo Way, Downingtown, Chester County PA",Siblings:"Annalyn · Bridget",CodingStart:"Started coding at 14, building Minecraft plugins",Education:"Computer science, West Chester University",EarlyCareer:"eMoney Advisor; DraftKings Inc.",Helicone:"Co-founded with Justin Torre, YC W23 (2023)",Mintlify:"Joined Mintlify after it acquired Helicone, 2026; leads an engineering team",Side:"DebateAI (AI debate platform)",Now:"San Francisco, CA"},story:["Cole grew up in the house on Santillo Way in Downingtown, a Chester County town, the son of Brian and Laurie and brother to Annalyn and Bridget. He was fourteen when he started writing code, building Minecraft plugins, and he stayed close for it, computer science at West Chester University, fifteen minutes south. The kid who tinkered after school never really stopped.","These days he lives in San Francisco. He worked at eMoney Advisor and DraftKings, then he and Justin Torre built Helicone, which went through Y Combinator in early 2023 and was acquired by Mintlify in 2026, where he now leads an engineering team. On the side he made DebateAI. When he's off the screen he cooks his way through Kenji Lopez-Alt and plays basketball."],src:["colegottdank.com (portfolio: started coding at 14 via Minecraft plugins; cooking, basketball)","linkedin.com/in/colegottdank (career: eMoney Advisor, DraftKings)","foundertrace.com/companies/helicone_yc_w23 (co-founders Cole Gottdank & Justin Torre, YC W23)","mintlify.com/blog/mintlify-acquires-helicone (acquisition 2026; 16,000+ orgs served)","mintlify.com/blog/why-we-joined-mintlify (three years watching AI in production)","helicone.ai/blog/joining-mintlify (joining Mintlify post)","x.com/coleywoleyyy/status/2028881716899934663 (Cole's announcement: building the knowledge infrastructure layer for an agentic future)"]},
annalyn:{name:"Annalyn Gottdank",conf:"likely",years:"living",place:"Downingtown, PA",rel:"Daughter of Brian & Laurie",facts:{Raised:"Santillo Way, Downingtown, Chester County PA",Siblings:"Cole · Bridget",Married:"Kyle Graefe, May 29, 2022",Work:"Customer Service Associate, Wawa, Downingtown PA",Stayed:"The sibling who remained near Downingtown, while Cole went to San Francisco and Bridget to Tel Aviv"},story:["Of Brian and Laurie's three, Annalyn is the one who stayed. She grew up on Santillo Way in Downingtown, the Chester County town out west of Philadelphia, and she's still in that corner of it, near the same back roads and the same people. Cole went off to San Francisco. Bridget went the whole way to Tel Aviv.","She married Kyle Graefe at the end of May 2022, and she works at Wawa a few minutes from where she came up. The Gottdank name is rare enough that a Gottdank in this one borough is almost surely the middle of Brian and Laurie's three. Her brother and sister went looking for somewhere else. Annalyn stayed home."],gap:"Not yet tied to the household record by address by an independent record.",src:["Zola registry (annalynandkyle): wedding date May 29, 2022","LinkedIn: Customer Service Associate, Wawa, Downingtown PA","Public people-records: parents Brian R & Laurie A (Cassidy) Gottdank; sister Bridget R Gottdank","brian/laurie/cole/bridget tree entries (Santillo Way upbringing; Cole to San Francisco; Bridget to Tel Aviv)"]},
bridget:{name:"Bridget Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Downingtown, PA → Tel Aviv, Israel",rel:"Daughter of Brian & Laurie · Cole and Annalyn's sister",facts:{Siblings:"Cole (San Francisco) · Annalyn (near Downingtown)",Background:"Raised in an interfaith household outside Philadelphia; found her own way to Judaism through Tikkun Olam",Education:"West Chester University, BA, political science & public policy; senior thesis: 'Religious Nationalism versus Democracy'",Aliyah:"Made aliyah from Philadelphia, late 2021 or early 2022; settled in Tel Aviv",Work:"Recruitment & Marketing Manager, Yahel Israel; founder of the design studio Anava Creative",Vote:"Cast her first Israeli ballot, November 2022"},story:["Of Brian and Laurie's three, Bridget went the farthest. She grew up in an interfaith house outside Philadelphia, in Downingtown, and found her own way to Judaism through Tikkun Olam, the work of repairing the world. Cole landed in San Francisco. Annalyn stayed near the Chester County back roads they all came up on. Bridget kept going, all the way across an ocean.","She first touched the country in the summer of 2019, on a Yahel fellowship in Haifa, the year after her West Chester thesis argued religious nationalism against democracy in the place she'd soon call home. She made aliyah from Philadelphia around the turn of 2022 and settled in Tel Aviv, where she recruits for Yahel and runs a small design studio of her own, Anava Creative. In November 2022 she cast her first Israeli ballot. Gittel's great-great-granddaughter, voting in a country her Galician ancestors never reached."],src:["LinkedIn (Bridget Gottdank; Tel Aviv District; Yahel Israel; BA West Chester, political science and applied public policy; Onward Israel fellowship, Haifa, summer 2019)","Yahel Israel team bios (thesis: 'Religious Nationalism versus Democracy'; interfaith background; Tikkun Olam; recruitment role)","Anava Creative (anavacreative.co)","JTA / Times of Israel, Nov 2022 (aliyah from Philadelphia, approx. 10 months before article, so late 2021 or early 2022; first Israeli election Nov 2022)"]},
dale:{name:"Dale D. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Brooklyn → San Diego (1989)",rel:"Son of Milton & Phyllis (likely)",facts:{Born:"Brooklyn, NY",Education:"Princeton, architecture grad 1979",Move:"San Diego 1989 · joined UUFSD summer 1990",Roles:"UUFSD board, president · Personnel Committee chair",Club:"Torrey Pines Gulls, secretary & communications officer (2022)"},story:["On a clear day Dale is up on the cliffs above Torrey Pines, easing a model glider off the edge into the wind coming up off the Pacific. He was born in Brooklyn, one of the two sons Milton and Phyllis raised to grown men, and he met Nancy Hebert at Princeton, he in architecture, she in urban planning. They married. In 1989 they left his hometown for San Diego and stayed.","They raised their son Jordan there, in and around the Unitarian Universalist Fellowship of San Dieguito in Solana Beach, which Dale joined in 1990 and has given decades to since, a long run on the board and a turn as its president. The other half of his life is the Torrey Pines Gulls, the soaring club where he keeps the records and the newsletter going. He trained to make buildings that hold still. What he loves is the thing that won't, a glider off a cliff, riding the same ocean air all afternoon."],src:["Princeton University Graduate Alumni Records (Department of Architecture, 1979): findingaids.princeton.edu/catalog/AC105-04_c9223","UUFSD 'Your Search Committee' bio (uufsd.org): met at Princeton, San Diego 1989, joined UUFSD 1990, board president, Personnel Committee; Jordan grew up at UUFSD; RE Committee chair Nancy 1990-2012","ZoomInfo (Chair, Personnel, UUFSD; Solana Beach, CA)","torreypinesgulls.org (secretary & communications officer, elected Feb 2022)","The New RC Soaring Digest, Oct 2022 (Dale Gottdank, 'Club in Focus: Torrey Pines Gulls')","La Jolla Light, Jan 7 2022 (proposed nighttime closures, Torrey Pines Gliderport)","LocateFamily (Brooklyn + San Diego)"]},
nancy:{name:"Nancy Hebert",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"San Diego, CA",rel:"Wife of Dale · deep American roots",facts:{Met:"Dale at Princeton; she was studying urban planning",Move:"Brooklyn first (Dale's hometown), then San Diego 1989",Career:"Healthcare finance, Scripps then Kaiser Permanente 25+ years",UUFSD:"Religious Education chair 1990-2012, the arc of Jordan's childhood; later Governance (P&P) chair",Son:"One grown son, Jordan, settled back in San Diego; Jordan's wife is Jessica",Name:"Hebert is the most common French surname in Louisiana (6,000+ households), descended from Acadian refugees of the 1760s-80s, themselves descendants of the brothers Antoine and Etienne Hebert of pre-expulsion Acadia"},story:["Nancy met Dale at Princeton, she in urban planning and he in architecture, and after a first married stretch in his native Brooklyn they went west in 1989 to one corner of coastal San Diego and stayed. They raised one son, Jordan, who grew up inside the Unitarian Universalist Fellowship of San Dieguito, where Nancy ran the children's religious education program from 1990 to 2012, the full arc of his childhood, and where she later chaired the governance side. Healthcare finance paid the bills, a quarter century of it at Kaiser.","The name she was born with is older on this continent than the one she married into. Hebert is the most common French surname in Louisiana, more than 6,000 households, carried there by the Acadian families the British drove out of Nova Scotia in 1755, and nearly all of them trace back to two brothers, Antoine and Etienne Hebert, in the Acadia of the 1600s. By 1766 five Hebert households had settled the first Acadian coast of the Mississippi above New Orleans. Gottdank crossed from Galicia in 1909. Hers had been here the better part of three centuries before that. She married a name that had just arrived, and carried one that was already old."],src:["UUFSD 'Your Search Committee' bio (uufsd.org, 2019-2020): met Dale at Princeton (urban planning), Brooklyn then San Diego 1989, Scripps then Kaiser Permanente 25+ yrs, Religious Education chair 1990-2012, one son Jordan, who with wife Jessica settled back in San Diego","uufsd.org Jan 2026 order of service: Nancy Hebert, Chair, P&P Governance","forebears.io/surnames/hebert: Hebert is Louisiana's most frequent surname of French origin (6,000+ households); practically all Louisiana Heberts descend from Acadian refugees who arrived 1760s-1780s, descendants of the brothers Antoine and Etienne Hebert; five Hebert families on the First Acadian Coast by 1766","Acadian Genealogy (acadian.org), 1671 census of the Hebert families: the brothers Antoine and Etienne Hebert came to Port Royal, Acadia about 1648","Acadian Expulsion of 1755 (British deportation of the Acadians from Nova Scotia)"]},
jordan:{name:"Jordan E. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"San Diego, CA",rel:"Son of Dale & Nancy · patent attorney",facts:{Family:"Dale & Nancy's only son; married to Jessica; settled back in San Diego",Education:"Physics BA, Oberlin College (2010) · JD, UCLA Law",Work:"Patent attorney, partner at Knobbe Martens (San Diego) since 2022"},story:["Jordan is Dale and Nancy's only son, raised on the coast above San Diego, in and out of the Unitarian Universalist fellowship in Solana Beach where his mother Nancy ran the children's religious-education program the whole length of his childhood. He went east to Oberlin for a physics degree, then up to Los Angeles for law school, and then he came home. He and his wife Jessica settled on the same stretch of California shore he grew up on.","He's a patent attorney now, and he made partner on the first day of 2022. His father Dale trained to draw buildings that hold still. Jordan, the physics major, watches the small true details that have to hold up. Same coast, a town his parents picked in 1989 and he chose again."],src:["Knobbe Martens professional profile (Jordan E. Gottdank, BA physics Oberlin, JD UCLA Law, co-founded IP Law Association, judicial extern on patent cases, joined 2015, partner Jan 1 2022)","Knobbe Martens, 'Best Lawyers: Ones to Watch' (Patent Law 2024-2025; Patent Litigation 2025)","UUFSD 'Your Search Committee' bio (uufsd.org): one son Jordan, raised in the fellowship, settled back in San Diego with wife Jessica","LocateFamily (Kibbings Rd household)"]},
jessica:{name:"Jessica Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"San Diego, CA",rel:"Wife of Jordan · married into the family",facts:{Married:"Jordan Gottdank, Dale & Nancy's son; she carries the rare Gottdank name by marriage",Home:"The San Diego coast, where Jordan grew up; she moved back to San Diego in 2015",Education:"BA, Oberlin College; BS, Olin College of Engineering",Work:"Aerospace engineer and program manager; PMP-certified",ACappella:"Directed the Olin PowerChords in college, led a Los Angeles group called Premiere, then founded the San Diego vocal band Voxy in 2015",Award:"Best Original Arrangement at the 2018 Los Angeles Harmony Sweepstakes ('Anthem Medley'); executive producer of the LA A Cappella Festival"},story:["Jessica married Jordan Gottdank and took the Gottdank name, and the two of them made their home on the stretch of San Diego coast where he grew up. She'd come up by way of a liberal arts college and an engineering school a thousand miles apart, a BA from Oberlin and a BS from Olin, and in 2015 she came back to San Diego for good. It's her home too.","The thing that's really hers is a cappella, music built out of nothing but voices. She directed the Olin PowerChords in school, led a group called Premiere through her Los Angeles years, and when she got to San Diego in 2015 and found no grown-up group to sing with, she started one and named it Voxy. In 2018 one of her arrangements won Best Original Arrangement at the Los Angeles Harmony Sweepstakes. By day she's an aerospace engineer. The rest of the time she's home on the coast, making songs out of breath and the people around her."],src:["UUFSD 'Your Search Committee' bio (uufsd.org): Dale & Nancy's one son Jordan settled back in San Diego with wife Jessica","boldjourney.com Meet Jessica Gottdank profile: raised toward music, BA Oberlin and BS Olin College of Engineering, directed the Olin PowerChords, founded/directed LA group Premiere, moved back to San Diego in 2015 and founded Voxy, aerospace engineer, LA A Cappella Festival","harmony-sweepstakes.com/details/1880 (Voxy: Gottdank/Todd/Liu; 2018 LA Best Original Arrangement, 'Anthem Medley')","LinkedIn jessica-gottdank: BA Oberlin / BS Olin College of Engineering; aerospace program management; PMP","Rare-surname reasoning: a Jessica Gottdank in San Diego carrying the Gottdank name matches the wife the UUFSD bio names for Jordan, San Diego's other Gottdank household"]},
bernhard:{name:"Bernhard Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"~1882 – 1917",place:"Galicia → Chicago, IL",rel:"Charles's brother · Gittel & Coleman's son",facts:{Born:"~1882, Galicia (the Isterik shtetl country), son of Kalman & Gittel",Brother:"Charles the New York barber; Bernhard took the family west to Chicago",Married:"Bertha Wiesenfeld, 1900; her people were from Kańczuga in central Galicia",Trade:"Chicago shopkeeper, photographed in front of his store",Settled:"Chicago's near West Side, the Maxwell Street immigrant district",Children:"Ruth · Kate · twins Helen & Florence (died as infants) · Mildred, all daughters",Twins:"Helen & Florence died as infants, buried at Jewish Waldheim, Forest Park",Died:"1917, about thirty-five"},story:["There's one photograph of Bernhard, a young man standing in front of his own shop in Chicago, and it's nearly the whole of what he left. He came out of Galicia the same as his brother Charles, the same shtetl country in the far southeast, but where Charles took a barber's razor to New York, Bernhard took a shopkeeper's counter to Chicago.","He landed on the near West Side, where the Galician and Russian Jews crowded in around Maxwell Street, forty synagogues and a market of pushcarts and kosher butchers they called the Ellis Island of the Midwest. In 1900 he married Bertha Wiesenfeld, of a family from Kańczuga, another corner of Galicia from his own town. They filled the flat with daughters: Ruth, Kate, the twins Helen and Florence, and Mildred.","He didn't get long. The twins died as infants and were laid at Jewish Waldheim out in Forest Park, and in 1917 Bernhard followed them, about thirty-five. He had carried a rare name across an ocean to Chicago, and every child he had was a girl. So the name went no farther west than his shop. It traveled on instead through his brother Charles's boys in New York, and Bernhard's part was the photograph, and the daughters, and the sound of that name spoken a little longer on the West Side."],src:["Family document, Generations 2-3","AncientFaces, Gottdank family (photo of Bernhard before his shop; children Ruth, Kate, twins Helen & Florence, Mildred)","FindAGrave (Bernard Gottdank, 1882-1917)","Encyclopedia of Chicago / History of the Jews in Chicago (Galician & Russian Jews on the near West Side; Maxwell Street market, the 'Ellis Island of the Midwest', ~40 synagogues)","bertha entry (Wiesenfeld of Kańczuga, Rzeszów district)","ruthM entry (West Fulton Street, near West Side)"]},
bertha:{name:"Bertha (Wiesenfeld) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1878 – 1967",place:"Galicia → Chicago, IL",rel:"Wife of Bernhard · of the shtetl's other family",facts:{Born:"June 22, 1878, a Wiesenfeld of Kańczuga, central Galicia",Married:"Bernhard Gottdank, 1900, at twenty-two",Shtetl:"Wiesenfeld traces to Kańczuga near Rzeszów; Aaron & Samuel Wiesenfeld helped charter the First Kanczuger Society, NYC 1902",Daughters:"Ruth · Kate · Mildred; twins Helen & Florence lost as infants",Widowed:"1917, at thirty-nine, when Bernhard died; she never remarried",Died:"Oct 14, 1967, aged eighty-nine, fifty years a widow"},story:["Bertha Wiesenfeld married Bernhard Gottdank in 1900, at twenty-two. Seventeen years later she buried him, daughters still to raise and most of her own life still in front of her. She never married again.","She was a Wiesenfeld, of Kańczuga, a market shtetl near Rzeszów in central Galicia, clear across the province from the Gottdanks' Isterik down in the southeastern hills. So the old family notion that the two clans came up out of one town is wrong. Bernhard and Bertha married the breadth of Galicia apart, not down one lane. When Kańczugers reached New York, it was Wiesenfelds, Aaron and Samuel, who helped charter the First Kanczuger Society in 1902 to carry the sick and the broke of the old town.","In Chicago she and Bernhard had Ruth and Kate and Mildred, and lost the twins, Helen and Florence, as infants. Then in 1917 Bernhard was gone, about thirty-five, and Bertha was a widow at thirty-nine. Born on the twenty-second of June, 1878, she died in October 1967, eighty-nine years old. She stayed a widow for fifty of them, half a century spent keeping a dead man's rare name."],src:["Family document","SSDI (Bertha Gottdank, b. June 22, 1878, d. 1967)","Gesher Galicia Family Finder (Wiesenfeld, Kańczuga / Rzeszów district)","kanczuga.org, First Kanczuger Society (chartered NYC Jan 8, 1902; founding directors include Aaron Wiesenfeld & Samuel Wiesenfeld)","AncientFaces (Bertha Gottdank of Chicago, b. June 22 1878, d. October 1967, aged 89)","FindAGrave (Bertha Wiesenfeld Gottdank, d. 1967)","bernhard entry (married 1900; daughters Ruth, Kate, twins Helen & Florence, Mildred; Bernhard d. 1917)"]},
ruthM:{name:"Ruth (Gottdank) Marek",conf:"verified",years:"b. ~1910",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Daughter of Bernhard & Bertha",facts:{Eldest:"Oldest of Bernhard & Bertha's Chicago daughters; a girl when her father died in 1917",Husband:"Michael Marek (1906–1979), a Chicago machinist; his parents came from Poland",HisWork:"Most of his working life at the Continental Can Company, retiring in the early 1970s",Children:"Jewel (b. 1935) · twins Donald & Bernard",Home:"West Fulton Street, Chicago's near West Side, from before WWII into the 1960s"},story:["Ruth was the oldest of Bernhard and Bertha's Chicago daughters, still a girl in 1917 when her father died. She came up in her mother's long widowhood, on the near West Side where the Galician Jews had crowded in.","She married Michael Marek, a Chicago machinist whose people had come from Poland. He gave most of his working life to the Continental Can Company. The two of them kept a house on West Fulton Street from before the war into the 1960s, and they raised three there: Jewel, born in 1935, and then the twin boys, Donald and Bernard.","That a Bernard turns up among those boys is the quiet thing about Ruth. Her father was gone before she was grown, and the name he'd carried out of Galicia ran out with his daughters. So she set it back down, in the middle of a Chicago boy, and the man in the one photograph kept a little ground in the city after all."],src:["Family document, Generation 4","AncientFaces (Michael Marek, b. May 30 1906, d. 1979, Chicago machinist at Continental Can Co., parents from Poland, Fulton Street home; wife Ruth Gottdank Marek; children Jewel b. 1935, twins Donald & Bernard)","bernhard / bertha entries (Ruth daughter of Bernhard & Bertha; Bernhard d. 1917; family on Chicago's near West Side)"]},
kateB:{name:"Kate (Gottdank) Bierlein",conf:"verified",years:"20th c.",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Daughter of Bernhard & Bertha",facts:{Order:"Second of Bernhard & Bertha's surviving daughters, between Ruth and Mildred",Father:"Bernhard died in 1917 when the girls were small; raised in Bertha's long widowhood, Chicago",Husband:"Ken Bierlein",Children:"Bernadine · Allen",Namesake:"Her daughter Bernadine, like Ruth's son Bernard, carries their father Bernhard's name forward"},story:["Kate was the second of Bernhard and Bertha's surviving daughters, between Ruth and Mildred. Her father died in 1917, when the girls were small, so she grew up the way her sisters did, inside Bertha's long widowhood in Chicago.","She married Ken Bierlein and had two, Bernadine and Allen. Look at that first name. Her sister Ruth had a boy and called him Bernard, and Kate had a girl and called her Bernadine. The Gottdank surname ran out with Bernhard's daughters, but the man's own name did not. Between them, his girls spelled it forward into the next generation, a Bernard in one Chicago house and a Bernadine in another."],src:["Family document, Generation 4","ruthM entry (sister Ruth named a son Bernard)","bernhard entry (father Bernhard, d. 1917; all his children daughters)"]},
twinsHF:{name:"Helen & Florence Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"died young",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Twin daughters of Bernhard & Bertha",facts:{Born:"May 24, 1913",Died:"Florence on Sept 16, Helen on Sept 17, 1913",Rest:"Jewish Waldheim Cemetery, Forest Park, outside Chicago"},story:["Bernhard and Bertha's twins, born together on the twenty-fourth of May, 1913. They lived not quite four months. Florence died on the sixteenth of September, Helen the next day, and they were buried at Jewish Waldheim in Forest Park."],src:["Family document, Generation 3","FindAGrave (Helen & Florence Gottdank, b. May 24 1913, d. Sept 16 & 17 1913, Waldheim Cemetery, Forest Park, IL)"]},
mildredH:{name:"Mildred (Gottdank) Harris",conf:"verified",years:"~1912 – 2006",place:"Wilmette, IL",rel:"Daughter of Bernhard & Bertha",facts:{Born:"~1912, Chicago, the youngest of Bernhard & Bertha's surviving daughters",Father:"Bernhard died in 1917, when she was small; raised in Bertha's long widowhood",Married:"Dr. Harold M. Harris, D.D.S.",Lived:"Wilmette, on Chicago's North Shore",Sons:"Bruce (Karen), Irvine CA · Irwin F. (June), Austin TX",Grandchildren:"Anna Popp · Stacie Bartfeld · Loren, Bradley & Jason Harris",Died:"March 2006, aged 94, the last of Bernhard & Bertha's children",Rest:"Shalom Memorial Park, Arlington Heights, IL"},story:["Mildred was the youngest of Bernhard and Bertha's daughters. She was small when her father died in 1917, and she came up in her mother's long widowhood.","She married Harold Harris, a dentist, and went north. They settled in Wilmette, up on the North Shore, a long way from the immigrant streets she'd grown up on, and raised two sons, Bruce and Irwin, who in time scattered west and south to Irvine and Austin. Grandchildren came after, Popps and Bartfelds and Harrises.","She made it to ninety-four. When she died in the spring of 2006, by the family's count the last of Bernhard and Bertha's children, eighty-nine years had passed since her father, the Galician shopkeeper, was gone. The youngest daughter carried their names the farthest, all the way into a new century."],src:["Family document","Chicago Tribune / Legacy.com, Mildred B. Harris obituary, Mar 24 2006 (nee Gottdank, age 94; wife of the late Dr. Harold M. Harris D.D.S.; sons Bruce (Karen) of Irvine CA and Irwin F. (June) of Austin TX; daughter of the late Bernhard and Bertha Gottdank; grandchildren Anna Popp, Stacie Bartfeld, Loren, Bradley & Jason Harris; graveside at Shalom Memorial Park, Arlington Heights)","bernhard / bertha entries (parents; Bernhard d. 1917)"]},
pauline:{name:"Pauline (Gottdank) Ascher",conf:"verified",years:"19th–20th c.",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Charles's sister · Generation 2",facts:{Parents:"Kalman & Gittel, Generation One",Siblings:"Charles the New York barber · Bernhard the Chicago shopkeeper · Clara, the other Chicago sister",Married:"an Ascher",Son:"went by Kermit Green"},story:["Pauline crossed from the Isterik shtetl country, the far southeast corner of Galicia, and she landed in Chicago the way her brother Bernhard did, two of Gittel's children setting up in the same city while Charles carried the barber's razor to New York. She came into the Galician Chicago of pushcarts and kosher butchers and crowded flats, where the old country put itself back together on a new map. She married a man named Ascher.","In this family the name came down through the women. It didn't come down through her. Her son grew up and called himself Kermit Green, an Ascher who'd shed even that for something plainer, the way a lot of them did once they were a generation deep into America. Nobody's found where Pauline herself sits in Cook County yet. So the clearest thing she left behind is a boy who started over with a brand new name, the daughter whose line let the old name go."],src:["Family document, Generations 2–3","Encyclopedia of Chicago / History of the Jews in Chicago (Galician Jewish immigrant district, near West Side / Maxwell Street)"]},
claraK:{name:"Clara Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"19th–20th c.",place:"Chicago, IL",rel:"Charles's sister · Generation 2",facts:{Parents:"Kalman & Gittel, Generation One",Married:"into the Korman family",Children:"Lena (Korman) Sandman · Karl Korman",Grandchildren:"Lena & Jacob Sandman's seven children, among them Albert Sandman (1925-2019)",Trade:"The Sandmans ran the Chicago scrap-and-detinning firm J. Sandman and Sons",Albert:"b. Jan 21, 1925; Army Air Corps in the Pacific in WWII; d. April 6, 2019, Tucson, AZ, aged 94"},story:["Clara married a Korman and made her life in Chicago, the same city her brother Bernhard ran a shop in while their brother Charles worked a barber's razor in New York. Her daughter Lena married Jacob Sandman. Her son was Karl Korman.","Lena and Jacob had seven kids, and the family went into scrap and detinning under the name J. Sandman and Sons. One of those seven was Albert, born in 1925, who flew the Pacific in the war and came home to the yard, loved the big bands and a long round of golf, and couldn't stand a bigot, treating every person he met as his equal. He died in Tucson in 2019 at ninety-four. Clara left almost no date behind her, and look how many people came from a woman we can barely name."],src:["Family document, Generations 2-4","Albert Sandman obituary, Shalom Memorial Funeral Home, 2019 (b. Jan 21 1925 to Jacob Sandman & Lena nee Korman; Army Air Corps, Pacific; family scrap-and-detinning business J. Sandman and Sons; loved big bands and golf; detested bigotry; d. April 6 2019, Tucson AZ, aged 94)","Geni (Jacob & Lena Sandman's children, indicating seven)"]},
yisroel:{name:"Israel ('Yisroel') Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1909 – 1985",place:"Isterik, Galicia → USSR → Leipheim DP camp → New York",rel:"Holocaust survivor · of the Isterik / Vaytman-Gottdank line",facts:{Origin:"Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne), Galicia, son of Abraham Weitman & Miriam Gottdank",Survived:"Survived the war in the Soviet Union, then Kyrgyzstan, then enlisted in the army",FirstWife:"Rukhl (née Kalb), born 1909 in Isterik, a tailor in Kraków; married 1933; she and their son Avrom were murdered",SecondWife:"Pnina, an Auschwitz and Ravensbrück survivor picked out of a selection line by Mengele; Miriam's mother (d. 1971)",ThirdWife:"later Shoshana (née Gomerov), a Lithuanian survivor who wrote her own memoir, 'An Uprooted Tree'",Daughter:"Miriam, born 1946 in Günzburg",Route:"Leipheim → Montreal (1948) → Crown Heights, Brooklyn (~1958) → d. New York 1985",Memoir:"Wrote a Yiddish memoir in 1984, the year before he died"},story:["Israel was born in Isterik in 1909. When the Germans came he fled east, into the Soviet Union, and that's how he lived.","His first wife came from his own town. Rukhl Kalb, born the same year as him, ran the book table at Isterik's literary club, and she was the one who put European writing in his hands. She moved to Kraków and worked as a tailor. They married in 1933 and had a son, Avrom. The last trace of her is a Nazi work card from February 1940. She and Avrom were murdered. She was thirty-one.","He started again. After the war he married Pnina, who had lived through Auschwitz, where Mengele picked her out of a line, and then Ravensbrück. He took work as a guard at the Leipheim displaced-persons camp, and their daughter Miriam was born in 1946. They reached Montreal in 1948 and later Brooklyn. The year before he died, Israel wrote his life down in Yiddish, and Miriam, who became a Yiddish scholar, kept it and translated it. One piece she wrote was about Rukhl, the wife he lost, built around four surviving photographs."],gap:"Family memory had two things wrong: he was remembered as Charles's brother (he belongs to the Isterik / Vaytman-Gottdank line instead), and the camp was Leipheim, not Bergen-Belsen. The one thread still on a single source is the match between the death-index 'Israel Gottdank 1909–1985' and the Geni Isterik profile.",src:["Lilith Magazine, 'Four Photographs of Rukhl'","Moment magazine memoir (Mengele tractor factory)","An Uprooted Tree (USHMM, Shoshana Gomerov Gottdank)","Yiddish Book Center / Wexler oral history","SSDI (Israel Gottdank, 1909-1985, NY)"]},
miriamDC:{name:"Miriam Gottdank Isaacs",conf:"verified",years:"b. 1946, living",place:"Günzburg, Germany → Montreal → United States",rel:"Israel's daughter · Yiddish scholar",facts:{Born:"1946 in Günzburg, Germany, Mengele's hometown, while her parents were at the Leipheim DP camp",Education:"PhD in linguistics, Cornell; taught Yiddish at the University of Maryland for sixteen years, now retired",Work:"Yiddish scholar and educator; a native Yiddish speaker",Translated:"her father's 1984 memoir and Shoshana Gomerov's 'An Uprooted Tree'",Drew:"a portrait of her grandmother 'Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik' from family memory"},story:["Miriam was born in 1946 in Günzburg, the hometown of Josef Mengele, the man who two years before had picked her mother out of a line at Auschwitz. Her parents were at the Leipheim displaced-persons camp, and she came to Montreal as a toddler in 1948. Yiddish was her first language, the one her parents carried out of Europe.","She made a life out of it. She earned a doctorate in linguistics at Cornell and taught Yiddish at the University of Maryland for sixteen years before she retired, and she became the family's bridge to the European story. She translated her father Israel's memoir and another survivor's, 'An Uprooted Tree' by Shoshana Gottdank Gomerov. She drew her murdered grandmother, Maryem Gottdank, the midwife of Isterik, from the way the family remembered her, and she wrote about the women her father lost, his first wife Rukhl and their son. In the end she became the keeper of the family's lost ones, giving them words and faces again."],src:["Moment magazine memoir (Mengele tractor factory)","Lilith Magazine, 'Four Photographs of Rukhl'","Yiddish Book Center / Wexler oral history","Jewish Women's Archive, Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik","USHMM, Voices on Antisemitism"]},
unknownB:{name:"The Unknown Brother",conf:"likely",years:"19th–20th c.",place:"New York, Manhattan",rel:"Charles's brother · name forgotten",facts:{Clue:"'Involved with the artist community in Manhattan', the family document",Hypothesis:"The unplaced NY Gottdanks (Abraham, Arnold, Harry, Samuel & Anna) may be his family",Manhattan:"Of those, Arnold Gottdank (Dec 18, 1895 - Nov 1975) is recorded living in Manhattan, the one address that fits the art-world clue"},story:["He ran with the artists in Manhattan. That's the whole inheritance, no name, no dates, just that. He was a sixth sibling, Charles's brother, out of the same Isterik shtetl country down in southeast Galicia, and somewhere around the turn of the century he turned up downtown, in the cheap rooms and easy streets that pulled in painters and poets and immigrants with more nerve than money. A Galician Jew threading through the Greenwich Village crowd, and not one word of him kept but that.","He may not have gone childless. The unplaced New York Gottdanks, Abraham over in Brooklyn, Arnold who actually lived in Manhattan, Anna, Sophie, all came from somebody, and he's the best guess going. And here's the cruel arithmetic of it. This was a family that guarded its name on purpose, passing it down through Gittel and through Miriam, the women who carried it to their husbands. The surname almost certainly outlived him in his own children. The one thing that didn't survive was him."],gap:"Name unknown. The 1910-1940 censuses for NY Gottdank households would likely surface him.",src:["Family document, Generation 2","AncientFaces / SSDI: New York Gottdank records (Abraham, Brooklyn, 1884-1975; Arnold, Manhattan, 1895-1975; Anna, Bronx, 1887-1980; Sophie, Queens, 1889-1984)"]},
abrahamW:{name:"Abraham Weitman Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"19th c.",place:"Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne), Galicia",rel:"Married into the name · father of Israel the survivor",facts:{Original:"Born a Vaytman/Weitman",Wife:"Miriam GOTTDANK, the name came from her",Children:"Israel the survivor, and Joseph (a shoemaker who stayed in Isterik), Rony, Calmen & Moyshe Aaron, the brothers murdered in the Shoah",Siblings:"David, Jacob & Heynekh Vaytman; Jenny Weitman, and a 'Weitmann' family appears in the Isterik martyr list"},story:["Abraham was born a Vaytman, and the name Gottdank reached him through his wife. He married Miriam Gottdank in Isterik, the shtetl tucked into the far southeast corner of Galicia, and he took her name. Kalman did the same, stepping into Gittel's name. Two couples in one small town, the same rare custom of a husband carrying the wife's name.","Their sons were Israel, who lived through the war off east in the Soviet Union, and Joseph the shoemaker, who stayed in Isterik, and Rony and Calmen and Moyshe Aaron. All but Israel were murdered in the Shoah. Whether Miriam was Gittel's own daughter or nearer kin, nobody knows. That unknown is the seam where the two Gottdank lines almost touch, same rare name, same town, same way of handing it down. Isterik's Jewish community is gone now, and the link sits there still, a hand's breadth from closing."],gap:"Miriam's parents, the missing link to Gittel's family, are not in any indexed record yet.",src:["Geni (Vaytman-Gottdank family of Isterik, documented by Miriam Gottdank Isaacs; children Israel, Joseph, Rony, Calmen & Moyshe Aaron)","Sefer Yizkor: Linsk, Istrik, Beligrod, Litovisk (Weitmann martyrs)"]},
miriam:{name:"Miriam Gottdank (of Isterik)",conf:"verified",years:"19th c. – 1942",place:"Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne), Galicia",rel:"The Gottdank-born wife of Abraham Vaytman",facts:{Trade:"Midwife of Isterik; her granddaughter drew her in a white apron, 'Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik'",Husband:"Abraham Vaytman, who took her Gottdank name at marriage",Sons:"Israel · Joseph · Rony · Calmen · Moyshe Aaron",Pattern:"Her husband took her name, like Coleman took Gittel's",Fate:"Deported autumn 1942 to the Zasław camp near Sanok, then Bełżec; the Isterik memorial book lists her as Miriam Weitmann"},story:["Her granddaughter drew her in a white apron and wrote the name underneath, Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik. She caught the babies of that shtetl in the far southeast corner of Galicia, where Jews had lived since the 1600s. The odd thing was the name itself. She was born a Gottdank, and when she married Abraham Vaytman, he took her name instead. Down the same streets Kalman had done it for Gittel. In Isterik the rare name came down through the women.","She and Abraham raised five sons, Israel, Joseph, Rony, Calmen, and Moyshe Aaron. In the autumn of 1942 the Germans emptied Isterik of its Jews and marched them to the Zasław camp near Sanok, then put them on trains to Bełżec. Maryem was murdered there. The memorial book sets her down under the married name she carried, Miriam Weitmann. Only Israel got out, east into the Soviet Union. Years later his daughter, another Miriam, drew her grandmother back from the way the family remembered her, white apron and all, the woman whose name they still carry."],src:["Geni family tree","Family document (naming parallel)","Jewish Women's Archive, 'Women Religious Workers in Eastern Europe' (Maryem Gottdank, midwife of Isterik, drawn by her granddaughter Miriam Isaacs in a white apron)","Sefer Yizkor: Linsk, Istrik (Miriam Weitmann, martyr list)","Virtual Shtetl (POLIN), Ustrzyki Dolne","Bełżec deportation list (Sanok district, Sept 1942)"]},
israel:{name:"Israel Gottdank, the survivor",conf:"verified",years:"1909 – 1985",place:"Isterik → USSR → Leipheim → New York",rel:"Son of Abraham & Miriam · the same man the family called 'Yisroel'",facts:{Born:"August 28, 1909, Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne), Galicia",Parents:"Abraham Vaytman & Miriam Gottdank, the town midwife",Survived:"Fled east into the Soviet Union; his mother and four brothers were murdered",Same:"The man the family remembered as 'Yisroel', one man, two memories now joined (full life in his own record)",Memoir:"Set his life down in Yiddish in 1984, the year before he died",Died:"New York, 1985",Daughter:"Miriam Gottdank Isaacs (b. 1946), the Yiddish scholar"},story:["Israel was born in Isterik on the twenty-eighth of August, 1909, a son of Abraham Vaytman and Miriam Gottdank, the town midwife. When the Germans came he ran east, deep into the Soviet Union, and that running is the reason he lived. His mother and four of his brothers did not.","For years the family kept him as two men, an Israel out of Kraków and a Yisroel they half remembered, before the two folded back into one. He reached New York and lived to 1985, and the year before he died he set his whole life down in Yiddish. His daughter Miriam, born in 1946, kept those pages. She carries her grandmother's name and the surname both, the Gottdank that came down through the women of Isterik."],src:["Moment magazine memoir","Yiddish Book Center oral history","Geni (Isterik / Vaytman-Gottdank)","SSDI (1909–1985, NY)"]},
joseph_g:{name:"Joseph · Rony · Calmen · Moyshe Aaron",conf:"likely",years:"early 20th c.",place:"Isterik (Ustrzyki Dolne), Galicia",rel:"Israel's siblings · murdered in the Shoah",facts:{Joseph:"'Yosl', a shoemaker who stayed in Isterik with his wife and small son; all murdered",Martyrs:"The Isterik Yizkor book names WEITMANN Yakov Yentche and Miriam among the town's dead, the family's Weitman name (no 'Gottdank' appears, fitting the matrilineal custom)",Documented:"Their profiles and the one surviving photo were entered by Israel's daughter, Miriam Gottdank Isaacs"},story:["Yosl kept his bench in Isterik, the shtetl folded into the far southeast corner of Galicia, mending shoes for a town that still had Jews in it. There's one photograph of him, the brother they called Joseph, with his wife and their small son at the edge of the frame. He stayed put. His brother Israel ran east and lived. Rony, Calmen, and Moyshe Aaron didn't get out.","In 1942 the town's Jews were taken to the Zasław camp near Sanok and on to Bełżec. The four brothers were murdered, and so were Joseph's wife and boy. The 1965 memorial book for Linsk and Istrik carries the Weitmann name among the murdered of Ustrzyki Dolne, never the Gottdank, because in this family the wife's name only ever attached at marriage. Israel was the one who got out, and his daughter Miriam set the names back down, so four brothers of a town that no longer holds any Jews are not entirely gone."],src:["Sefer Yizkor: Linsk, Istrik, Beligrod, Litovisk (Tel Aviv, 1965), martyr list, p. 478","Geni (Isterik / Vaytman-Gottdank, documented by Miriam Isaacs)","Zasław transit camp record","Bełżec deportation list (Sanok district, Sept 1942)"]},
davidO:{name:"David Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"~1880 – 1922",place:"London → Ottawa",rel:"Immigrant patriarch, Ottawa line",facts:{Married:"Rachel Leah Cohen, in London",Emigrated:"London to Ottawa, ~1905–1910, with daughters Sarah and the infant Esther; Jeanne, Arthur and Syd born in Ottawa",Census:"1911, Victoria Ward, Ottawa, with the children",Children:"Sarah (piano) · Esther (cello) · Jeanne (violin) · Arthur · Syd",Died:"August 31, 1922, tuberculosis, in his early forties",Buried:"Jewish Memorial Gardens, Bank Street, Ottawa",Line:"Through his son Arthur, the ancestor of every Gottdank in Canada"},story:["David married Rachel Cohen in London, and London was only a place to catch their breath. Sometime after 1905 the two of them crossed to Ottawa with little Sarah and Esther still in arms. By the spring of 1911 they'd settled into Victoria Ward with the children around them, and three more, Jeanne, Arthur, and Syd, were born on the Canadian side.","It was a house full of music almost from the start. The three girls went to their lessons young, Sarah to the piano, Esther to the cello, Jeanne to the violin, and a couple of them would later ride the American vaudeville circuit under a stage name. David lived to hear the beginning of it. The first scales, the wrong notes, the slow getting better. He never heard the applause.","Tuberculosis took him on the last day of August, 1922, barely into his forties. Rachel was left to raise the five on her own. They buried him in the Jewish ground on Bank Street, in a country he'd reached only a dozen-odd years before. But the name held. Through his one son, Arthur, every Gottdank in Canada traces back to the man who crossed an ocean with two little girls and started again."],src:["FindAGrave 256993440, citing Ottawa Jewish Archives","Canadian Jewish Heritage Network, Gottdank family fonds (cjhn80387): married in London, emigrated to Ottawa 1905-1910 with Sarah and infant Esther; Jeanne, Arthur, Syd born in Ottawa; daughters' early music lessons; David d. 1922, TB, early forties","Canadian Jewish Heritage Network, Gottdank family portrait (cjhn82997: Syd, David, Sarah, Arthur, Rachel Leah, Esther, Jeanne)","1911 Census of Canada (Victoria Ward, Ottawa)","Jewish Memorial Gardens, Ottawa (Bank Street)"]},
rachelO:{name:"Rachel Leah Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"d. 1938",place:"London → Ottawa",rel:"Immigrant matriarch, Ottawa line",facts:{Maiden:"Cohen, confirmed on her Ottawa gravestone (the Geni 'Nitupski' is wrong)",Died:"March 20, 1938",Widowed:"1922, with five children"},story:["Rachel was born in the Russian Empire around 1881 and married David in London, so London was the waypoint, not home. After he died in 1922 she raised Sarah, Esther, Jeanne, Arthur, and Syd on her own for sixteen years. She started all three daughters on music early, Sarah at the piano, Esther on cello, Jeanne on violin, and that decision put two of them on the American vaudeville circuit."],src:["FindAGrave 256993443","Geni (Rachel Gottdank profile)","1911 Census of Canada (Rachel born about 1881, Russia)"]},
estherO:{name:"Esther Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1904 – 1988",place:"Ottawa → vaudeville America",rel:"Daughter of David & Rachel · the touring cellist",facts:{Start:"Played silent-movie accompaniment, Allen's Danforth Theatre, Toronto",Stage:"'The Roumanian Serenaders' → 'The Slaves of Melody' (from ~1926)",StageName:"Performed as Esther GORDON",Married:"David Mirsky in NY, Jan 19 1932, kept secret to protect her Canadian tax-department job; nephew of Rev. Jacob Mirsky"},story:["Esther learned cello because her widowed mother insisted on it. She started in the orchestra pit at Allen's Danforth Theatre in Toronto, playing live to silent movies, then around 1926 joined a touring Chicago vaudeville troupe, the Roumanian Serenaders, later the Slaves of Melody, and rode the American circuit for five years.","On the road she and her sister went by a stage name, and it turns up in the papers: a 1927 Indiana bill lists 'the Gordon sisters, who play the violin and cello.' The Gottdank girls had become the Gordons. She came home to Ottawa, married David Mirsky in New York in 1932, and kept the wedding quiet to protect her job at the tax department. She played to the end of her life and was a life member of the city's musicians' union; she died in 1988. Her daughter Deborah later gave the family's papers, vaudeville schedules and all, to the Ottawa Jewish Archives, which is why so much of this branch survives."],src:["Geni / Ottawa Jewish Archives (Gottdank family fonds)","South Bend News-Times, Oct 23 1927 (the Gordon sisters)","Jewish Memorial Gardens, Ottawa (Esther Mirsky)"]},
jeanneO:{name:"Jeanne Gottdank Lieff",conf:"verified",years:"1906 – 2003",place:"Ottawa",rel:"Daughter of David & Rachel · violinist",facts:{Toured:"Joined the Serenaders with Esther ~1926; left after two years",StageName:"Performed as a 'Gordon' sister",Married:"Louis Lieff, brother of Justice Abraham H. Lieff (1903–2007)",Lived:"96 years"},story:["The violinist of the three sisters, in the Ottawa Philharmonic by the time she was thirteen. She toured vaudeville with Esther under the Gordon name for two years, then came home and married Louis Lieff, whose brother Abraham became the first Jewish justice of Ontario's Supreme Court. She kept playing in Ottawa's orchestras almost to her 97th birthday, in 2003."],src:["Geni / Ottawa Jewish Archives","Jewish Memorial Gardens, Ottawa (Jeanne Lieff)","Bill Gladstone, Justice Abraham Lieff at 100"]},
sasO:{name:"Sarah & Syd Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"early 1900s",place:"Ottawa",rel:"Children of David & Rachel",facts:{Sarah:"The pianist (1900–1958), married Harry Torontow, Nov 1925; sons David & Abraham Torontow",Syd:"Took the surname GORDON, the name his sisters toured under"},story:["Sarah, the eldest, was the pianist; she married Harry Torontow of Ottawa's well-known Torontow family in 1925 and had two sons, David and Abraham. She lived from 1900 to 1958. Their brother Syd took the surname Gordon, the same name his sisters performed under, which is why the Sidney Gottdank later found in Ridgecrest, California is probably a different man."],src:["Geni / Ottawa Jewish Archives","Torontow family fonds (CJHN)"]},
arthur:{name:"Arthur J. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1910 – 1983",place:"Ottawa, ON",rel:"Son of David & Rachel · father of the Canadian line",facts:{Born:"1910, Ottawa (after the family's ~1905–10 arrival)",Died:"1983, per his public FamilySearch profile (LBJ2-M7K)",Wife:"Violet Kathleen (~1925–2014)",Children:"Robert 'Bob' · David 'Lee' · Michael 'Kim' · Tina Lou"},story:["The one boy in that musical Ottawa house, and the one who carried the name on. While his sisters toured, Arthur stayed home, married Violet Kathleen, and raised four children. Every Gottdank in Canada today comes through them.","For a long time he was just a first name on the chart. Now he's bracketed by dates, 1910 to 1983. He was buried at Capital Memorial Gardens, a secular cemetery, not with his parents in the Jewish ground on Bank Street."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary, Ottawa Citizen, Apr 30 2014","FamilySearch profile LBJ2-M7K (Arthur J Gottdank, 1910-1983)","Capital Memorial Gardens, Ottawa (plot 330C-1)"]},
violet:{name:"Violet Kathleen Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"~1925 – 2014",place:"Ottawa, ON",rel:"Wife of Arthur · matriarch of the Canadian line",facts:{Maiden:"née Fisher, parents Thomas Fisher & Maria Durocher",Died:"April 28, 2014, Carleton Lodge, in her 89th year",Children:"Bob (Rita) · Lee (Joyce) · Kim (Janet) · the late Tina Lou (Rick)",Grandchildren:"Steven (Celina) · Danny (Celia) · Kayla (Thomas) · Lauren · Nathan",Also:"5 great-grandchildren; sisters Gladys & the late Lena",Rest:"Capital Funeral Home & Cemetery, Prince of Wales Dr"},story:["The hinge of the Canadian branch. Born Violet Fisher in 1925, she married Arthur, and through them two whole generations come into view, four children and five grandchildren, tying the modern Canadian Gottdanks back to the immigrant line. She died in 2014, in her 89th year; her headstone carries the crest of the IODE, the Imperial Order Daughters of the Empire.","Two more Gottdank women belong here too: Edith and Barbara, daughters-in-law who signed her guestbook 'in remembrance of our Mother-in-Law.'"],src:["Ottawa Citizen obituary, Apr 30 2014 (full text via Legacy.com)","Ancestry (Violet Fisher, born Aug 25 1925)"]},
bobG:{name:"Robert 'Bob' Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Thornhill, ON",rel:"Son of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Wife:"Rita (attended Perth & District Collegiate)",Confirmed:"Named 'Bob Gottdank of Thornhill' in sister Tina's 1987 death notice"},story:["The eldest son. When his sister Tina died in 1987, the Ottawa Citizen notice named him plainly, 'Bob Gottdank of Thornhill,' which settles that the Robert Gottdank up in that town north of Toronto is Arthur and Violet's boy. His wife Rita went to Perth and District Collegiate, out in the Lanark County town west of Ottawa, so the marriage reaches back into the family's own part of eastern Ontario. Edith Gottdank, a daughter-in-law of Arthur and Violet, lives in the same Thornhill area."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary","Ottawa Citizen, Tina Gottdank-Normoyle death notice, 1987 ('Bob Gottdank of Thornhill', brother)","LocateFamily (Thornhill records)"]},
davidGreely:{name:"David 'Lee' Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Greely, ON (Ottawa)",rel:"Son of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Named:"After his grandfather, the immigrant David",Wife:"Joyce",Location:"Greely, ten miles from his grandfather's grave"},story:["Violet's son David 'Lee,' with Joyce, lives in Greely, an Ottawa suburb ten miles from Jewish Memorial Gardens, where the first David Gottdank was buried in 1922. A grandson carrying his grandfather's name, just the way Jewish naming tradition would predict."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary (named son)","LocateFamily (Greely, ON)"]},
kimG:{name:"Michael 'Kim' Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Kemptville / Nepean, ON",rel:"Son of Arthur & Violet · entrepreneur",facts:{Wife:"Janet",Companies:"COM/MIT Financial · COM/MIT Hitech · Clean.Net Inc.",Area:"Kemptville, Lanark, Nepean, greater Ottawa"},story:["Violet's son Michael 'Kim,' with Janet. The 'M. Kim Gottdank' and 'Michael K. Gottdank' who own three companies out in the Ottawa countryside are the same man, the immigrants' grandson turned small-business owner."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary (named son)","CompaniesOfCanada / OpenCorporates: M. Kim Gottdank, director, COM/MIT Hitech Services Inc., Kemptville ON"]},
tinaG:{name:"Tina Louise Gottdank-Normoyle",conf:"verified",years:"~1959 – 1987",place:"Ontario",rel:"Daughter of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Died:"Friday, January 30, 1987, aged 27",Husband:"Richard 'Rick' Normoyle",Son:"Nathan",Survivors:"Mother Violet (Fisher) Gottdank; brother Bob of Thornhill"},story:["Arthur and Violet's daughter, lost young. She died on a Friday, January 30, 1987, at twenty-seven, leaving her husband Richard Normoyle and their son Nathan. The Ottawa Citizen notice named her as the daughter of Violet Fisher Gottdank and the late Arthur, with Bob of Thornhill her brother.","Her boy Nathan, one of the grandchildren listed in Violet's obituary years later, carries the line on."],src:["Ottawa Citizen death notice, Jan 31 1987 (Tina Louise Gottdank-Normoyle, age 27; wife of Richard Normoyle; mother of Nathan; daughter of Violet & the late Arthur)"]},
danny:{name:"Danny Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Toronto, ON",rel:"Grandson of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Wife:"Celia",Work:"Talent Acquisition Manager, Technology, Rogers Communications",Education:"York University",Lineage:"Great-great-grandson of David & Rachel"},story:["Danny runs technology recruiting at Rogers in Toronto, the hire-the-hirers job, pulling in network operations people, cloud engineers, cybersecurity advisors for the country's biggest telecom. He's Arthur's grandson and a great-great-grandson of the London couple who landed in Ottawa around 1905.","Four generations from the boat to the recruiter's desk, and the name made the whole trip."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary (named grandson)","Danny Gottdank LinkedIn (Talent Acquisition Manager, Technology, Rogers Communications)","LocateFamily"]},
celia:{name:"Celia Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living/recent",place:"Markham / Bradford, ON",rel:"Wife of Danny",facts:{Named:"'Danny (Celia)' in Violet's obituary",Household:"Breeze Drive, same address & phone as Danny"},story:["Danny's wife, written as 'Danny (Celia)' in Violet's 2014 obituary, which is how the Ottawa branch named its grandchildren's spouses. They share a household on Breeze Drive, north of Toronto. She marries into a line that runs back through Arthur in Ottawa to the couple who crossed from London around 1905."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary","LocateFamily (shared household)"]},
steven:{name:"Steven Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Toronto, ON",rel:"Grandson of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Wife:"Celina",Listed:"South Kingsway, Toronto"},story:["Violet's grandson, named 'Steven (Celina)' in her obituary, listed on South Kingsway in west-end Toronto. He's one of the handful of Arthur and Violet's grandchildren, the generation that moved the Canadian line off the Ottawa ground their great-grandparents settled and into the bigger city. The whole Toronto cluster in this tree traces back to that one Ottawa couple."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary (named grandson)","LocateFamily (Toronto)"]},
grandkidsCA:{name:"Kayla · Lauren · Nathan",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Ontario",rel:"Grandchildren of Arthur & Violet",facts:{Kayla:"married Thomas",Plus:"Five great-grandchildren by 2014"},story:["The rest of Violet's grandchildren. By 2014 the Canadian line had reached five great-grandchildren, a sixth living generation from David and Rachel's 1905 crossing."],src:["Violet Gottdank obituary"]},
torontoMisc:{name:"Edith & Barbara Gottdank",conf:"likely",years:"living/recent",place:"Thornhill, ON & Canton, MA",rel:"Daughters-in-law of Arthur & Violet (self-identified)",facts:{Evidence:"Signed Violet's guestbook: 'In remembrance of our Mother-in-Law'",Edith:"Thornhill / North York directory records",Barbara:"Canton, MA record"},story:["Two more living Gottdank women, Edith and Barbara, daughters-in-law of Arthur and Violet. Which sons they married is the open detail, though Edith's Thornhill address matches Robert's town."],gap:"Exact pairing to Violet's sons unstated.",src:["Violet obituary guestbook (self-identified)","LocateFamily records"]},
nyimm:{name:"Unplaced New York Gottdanks",conf:"verified",years:"b. 1884 – 1902",place:"Brooklyn · Bronx · Manhattan",rel:"Likely the Unknown Brother's family, or close kin",facts:{Members:"Abraham (1884–1975, Brooklyn) · Samuel ⚭ Anna (1887–1980) → Esther Brody · Sophie (1889–1984) · Annie (1890–1986) · Arnold (1895–1975, Manhattan) · Harry (1895–1975)",Households:"Two married Gottdank couples surface in the census: Benjamin ⚭ Sophie in the Bronx (→ Ruth, Mildred) and Louis ⚭ May (née Stillman) in Brooklyn (→ Mildred, Claire), likely the unknown brother's sons",Hypothesis:"The 'unknown brother' of Manhattan is the best candidate for their father"},story:["These New Yorkers are the leftover, and the forgotten sixth sibling, the one in the Manhattan art world, is the likeliest father or uncle. The dates settle into one set: Abraham, born 1884, died in Brooklyn at ninety; Sophie, 1889, out in Rockaway Park; Arnold, 1895, in Manhattan to the end. Two of them, Harry and Annie, turn up dying in Los Angeles, so part of this New York set went west.","The census is starting to sort them into households: a Benjamin Gottdank and family in the Bronx, a Louis Gottdank and family in Brooklyn, two married Gottdank men of the right age who are most likely the unknown brother's sons. The brother himself stays just out of reach."],src:["SSDI","1920-1950 US Census (Benjamin/Bronx, Louis/Brooklyn households)","AncientFaces (Gottdank death records)","Family document (unknown brother)"]},
nygen:{name:"NY-born, still unplaced",conf:"verified",years:"b. 1908 – 1924",place:"New York City",rel:"The rest of the American-born band",facts:{Members:"Gladys (1908) · Rosa (1910) · David (1911) · Mildred (1916) · Christine (1918) · Terry (1918) · Beatrice (1919) · Lawrence (1919) · Seymour (1920) · Leon (1922, buried at LA's Hillside) · Barbara (1924)",Placed:"Jerome=Jerry ✓ · Milton ✓ · Molly ✓ · Irving (El Cajon) likely Chicago-or-NY kin"},story:["Jerry and Milton stepped out of this anonymous band into the documented family. The rest are still waiting. Most are probably children of the unknown brother, or New York cousins of Charles, first cousins of Milton's generation who scattered later to Florida and California."],src:["Social Security Death Index","LA Times (Leon, Hillside Mortuary)"]},
lawrence:{name:"Lawrence Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1919 – 1998",place:"NY → Pompano Beach, FL",rel:"Plainview patriarch (inferred)",facts:{Born:"May 23, 1919",Died:"Oct 27, 1998"},story:["Born the same year as Beatrice and died in the Florida retirement belt. He's the natural father for the Plainview household, though the marriage is an inference, not a record."],gap:"Marriage to Beatrice inferred from matching years + Long Island geography.",src:["SSDI"]},
beatrice:{name:"Beatrice Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1919 – 2009",place:"Plainview, NY & Margate, FL",rel:"Plainview matriarch",facts:{Born:"July 4, 1919",Died:"Feb 8, 2009, aged 89"},story:["A Fourth-of-July baby who lived to eighty-nine and wintered in Margate, Florida. Her Plainview address is one street over from the household of Joseph, Ellen, Heather, and Tracy."],src:["SSDI","LocateFamily (Plainview & Margate)"]},
josephP:{name:"Joseph D. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Plainview, NY",rel:"Son of Lawrence & Beatrice (inferred)",facts:{Household:"29 Alma Lane, Plainview, with Ellen N., Heather A., Tracy S.",Phone:"One household line shared by all four (516) 639-4186"},story:["Head of the household at 29 Alma Lane in Plainview, the postwar Long Island suburb where a lot of New York Jewish families landed when they left the city. He's there with Ellen and their daughters Heather and Tracy, all four on the same phone line, the kind of detail that ties a family together in the public record even when nothing else does.","Beatrice's old address sat a street over, and the timing fits, so the likeliest read is that Joseph is Lawrence and Beatrice's son. No document spells the parentage out, so that part stays a careful guess."],gap:"Parentage inferred; no document names it.",src:["ClustrMaps / LocateFamily (29 Alma Lane: Joseph D., Ellen N., Heather A., Tracy S. Gottdank, shared phone)"]},
ellenP:{name:"Ellen Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Plainview, NY",rel:"Wife of Joseph",facts:{Household:"Alma Lane, Plainview"},story:["Ellen at 29 Alma Lane, the name beside Joseph's across two decades of Plainview records. Plainview was potato and pickle farmland until the early fifties, when builders threw up split-levels almost overnight and the new houses filled with young families leaving Brooklyn and Queens for a yard and a good school district. That is the world the Alma Lane household sits in, four names on one phone line, raising Heather and Tracy."],src:["LocateFamily","ClustrMaps (29 Alma Lane household)"]},
heather:{name:"Heather Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Plainview, NY",rel:"Daughter of Joseph & Ellen",facts:{Household:"Alma Lane, Plainview"},story:["One of the two daughters raised at 29 Alma Lane in Plainview, the postwar Long Island suburb of split-levels and good schools that drew young Jewish families out of the city. She and Tracy are the next generation of the household, listed on the same line as their parents."],src:["LocateFamily (shared household)"]},
tracy:{name:"Tracy Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Plainview / Franklin Sq, NY",rel:"Daughter of Joseph & Ellen",facts:{Household:"Alma Lane; later Franklin Square"},story:["The other daughter raised at 29 Alma Lane, and the one the record follows out the door: a later listing of her own in Franklin Square, a few towns west toward the Queens line. That short hop is the next Long Island generation setting out on its own, staying close to where it grew up."],src:["LocateFamily (shared household + Franklin Sq)"]},
roseEC:{name:"Rose (Tuchfeld) Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1902 – 1995",place:"Los Angeles → San Diego, CA",rel:"The Los Angeles matriarch",facts:{Born:"Dec 26, 1902, parents Morris Tuchfeld & Dora Schloss",Husband:"Harry Gottdank",Children:"Irving · Sydney (and Paul)",Died:"July 9, 1995, near San Diego"},story:["The mother of the California Gottdanks. Rose was born a Tuchfeld, married Harry Gottdank, and raised the family in Los Angeles; the 1940 and 1950 censuses put Harry and Rose there with their sons Irving and Sydney. She died near San Diego in 1995, at ninety-two."],src:["1940 & 1950 US Census, Los Angeles","SSDI","Rose Gottdank death record, San Diego 1995"]},
irving:{name:"Irving E. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"1925 – 2014",place:"Los Angeles → El Cajon, CA",rel:"Son of Harry & Rose · Milton's generation",facts:{Born:"September 11, 1925, to Harry & Rose (Tuchfeld) Gottdank, Los Angeles",Brother:"Sydney Gottdank",Died:"January 22, 2014, El Cajon",Address:"Alderson Street, El Cajon"},story:["Born in Los Angeles in 1925 to Harry and Rose Gottdank, Irving settled down the coast in El Cajon. He was four years younger than Milton and of the same American-born generation, a likely cousin, living out his years twenty minutes from Dale's San Diego without either side necessarily knowing.","His brother Sydney is very probably the Sidney Gottdank later found up in Ridgecrest."],src:["1940 & 1950 US Census, Los Angeles","Legacy.com obituary, Jan 22 2014"]},
sidney:{name:"Sidney Gottdank",conf:"likely",years:"living/recent",place:"Los Angeles → Ridgecrest, CA",rel:"Likely Harry & Rose's son · Irving's brother",facts:{Origin:"Very likely the 'Sydney' the Los Angeles census lists as Harry & Rose Gottdank's son, Irving's brother",Household:"Farragut Street, Ridgecrest, with Linda L.",Town:"Ridgecrest = the China Lake naval weapons base"},story:["Sidney and Linda shared a household in Ridgecrest, the desert town built around the China Lake weapons base, which hints at defense work. He's very likely the Sydney the Los Angeles census names as Harry and Rose's son, which would make him Irving's brother and tie Ridgecrest to the California family."],gap:"The Ridgecrest Sidney = LA Sydney match is strong (same name, same state, right family), but not pinned by a single record.",src:["1940 & 1950 US Census, Los Angeles (Harry & Rose → Sydney)","LocateFamily (Ridgecrest household)"]},
linda:{name:"Linda L. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living/recent",place:"Ridgecrest, CA",rel:"Wife of Sidney",facts:{Household:"Same Farragut St address"},story:["Linda L., listed with Sidney at the Farragut Street household across twenty years of records. Ridgecrest is a company town in the Mojave, built up around the Navy's China Lake weapons station, where most of the working population draws a government or contractor paycheck. That desert posting is about all the public record gives of the two of them, two names on one address far out in the California high desert."],src:["LocateFamily"]},
alex:{name:"Alex Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"San Juan Capistrano, CA",rel:"Author & teacher · OC cluster",facts:{Author:"'Preparing for Christ's New Name' (2004)",Faith:"Bahá'í, from a Jewish/Christian background",Service:"Nat'l Spiritual Assembly, W. Caroline Islands, 1988–2000"},story:["Alex grew up in a Jewish and Christian family and read the Gospel for the first time at sixteen. The questions it raised kept going. A three-year conversation with a Bahá'í friend about the return of Christ turned into his 2004 book, 'Preparing for Christ's New Name.' He spent twelve years on the Bahá'í National Spiritual Assembly of the Western Caroline Islands and taught at Yap High School in Micronesia, and he now teaches seventh-grade world history in San Juan Capistrano."],src:["Preparing for Christ's New Name (Naturegraph, 2004)","Alex Gottdank, BahaiTeachings.org author page"]},
marilyn:{name:"Marilyn B. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living/recent",place:"San Clemente / Vista, CA",rel:"OC cluster, likely Alex's household",facts:{Towns:"San Clemente & Vista, minutes from San Juan Capistrano"},story:["Marilyn lives in San Clemente, ten minutes from Alex's San Juan Capistrano, and Adam's household record names her alongside Alex and him. That ties the three south Orange County Gottdanks into one family; her exact place in it isn't written down."],gap:"Link to Alex inferred from tight geography only.",src:["LocateFamily (San Clemente/Vista)","ThatsThem (Adam's household lists Marilyn)"]},
adam:{name:"Adam S.U. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"Laguna Niguel, CA",rel:"OC cluster",facts:{Role:"Associate Dean & Director of Disability Support Services, North Orange County Community College District",Wrote:"co-author, 'Transition, A Conversation with Parents'",Home:"Laguna Niguel"},story:["Adam runs disability support services for the North Orange County Community College District, and co-wrote a guide for parents on a young person's transition to adult life. He lives in Laguna Niguel, and his household record lists Alex and Marilyn alongside him, which ties the three south Orange County Gottdanks into one family, even if the record doesn't spell out who is whose parent."],gap:"Cluster relationships inferred from geography.",src:["ThatsThem (Adam Gottdank household)","openpayrolls / LinkedIn"]},
michaelNJ:{name:"Michael D. Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living",place:"East Brunswick, NJ",rel:"Unplaced, New York roots",facts:{Career:"Managing Director, Equitas Advisors / Equitas Brokerage Group, East Brunswick NJ",Earlier:"Led carrier and solution sales across Western Europe for IDT",Education:"MBA, Tel Aviv University"},story:["Michael runs an insurance brokerage shop in East Brunswick, a managing director at Equitas, where he helps property-and-casualty agents add life, health, and financial planning to what they sell. Before that he was overseas for the telecom IDT, building and running its carrier-sales team across Western Europe, and he picked up his MBA at Tel Aviv University along the way.","He's a born New Yorker who landed in central New Jersey, and we can't yet pin his branch to the rest of the tree. The one New Jersey death record in the name, a Rosa Gottdank who lived from 1910 to 1987, might be his grandmother. That thread is still loose."],gap:"Unplaced; the Rosa Gottdank (NJ, 1910-1987) link is a guess, not a record.",src:["ZoomInfo / ContactOut (Michael D. Gottdank, Managing Director, Equitas Advisors, East Brunswick NJ; IDT Western Europe; Tel Aviv University MBA)","LocateFamily (East Brunswick)"]},
mariza:{name:"Mariza & Fernando Gottdank",conf:"verified",years:"living/recent",place:"São Paulo & Santos, Brazil",rel:"The Brazilian branch",facts:{Mariza:"Santos → São Paulo; founded the language school 'Dank Idiomas' in 2010",Fernando:"Fernando Adrian Gottdank, a São Paulo graphic designer who made aliyah in 2019; survived the Oct 7, 2023 attack at the Universo Paralello rave in Israel",Roots:"Her father was Ihdy Herch Alfabet, of a family that fled the Nazis to Brazil; the Gottdank name reaches her through her mother"},story:["The name reached South America. Mariza grew up poor in the port city of Santos; her father, Ihdy Herch Alfabet, died when she was thirteen, and an uncle paid for the English course that changed everything. She ran the elevator at the local newspaper, started teaching English on the side in 1993, moved to São Paulo, and in 2010 opened her own language school, Dank Idiomas, named off the back half of the family name.","Her father's people were Alfabet, refugees who fled the Nazis to Brazil, so the Gottdank name reaches her through her mother. Fernando Gottdank is the other Brazilian who carries it: a São Paulo graphic designer who made aliyah in 2019. He was at the Universo Paralello rave in the Israeli south on October 7, 2023, and got out alive, sheltering in a bunker and then driving clear of the festival the attack overran."],gap:"Which Gottdank emigrated to Brazil, and through which parent, is still open; Santos port records would resolve it.",src:["Dank Idiomas (Mariza Gottdank profile & interview)","Metrópoles, Oct 2023 (Fernando, Universo Paralello)","Behance (Fernando Gottdank portfolio)"]},
};
